The CDs were synthesized using a microwave-assisted method employing glucose as a precursor. These CDs were utilized as stabilizing and reducing agents during the preparation of AgNPs. The CDs are bound to the surface of AgNPs, forming what is CDs/AgNPs. The prepared nanoparticles were subsequently subjected to further characterization by FT-IR analysis, examination under a TEM microscope, and assessment of their optical properties. The FT-IR spectrum [ Fig. 3
(a)] highlighted the presence of hydroxyl groups with reducing activity on the surface of CDs. This property enables the CDs to act as electron donors in reactions involving electron-withdrawing agents. Moreover, the FT-IR spectrum confirms the presence of carboxyl groups on the surface of CDs, known for their strong affinity towards Ag+ ions. Therefore, these ions are probably adsorbed on the surface of CDs via carboxyl groups. Furthermore, the TEM image of the as-prepared CDs/AgNPs [ Fig. 3 (b)] revealed their spherical nature with sizes in the range of 5–20 nm. Additionally, the UV–vis absorption spectrum of the synthesized CDs/AgNPs exhibited an absorption band centered at a wavelength of 410 nm ( Fig. 4
).

The proposed sensor demonstrated excellent selectivity towards KTF, exhibiting negligible interference from common ophthalmic excipients in eye drops and from other components present in the aqueous humor, thus enhancing the accuracy of the analysis. This can be observed from the high % recovery from real samples (
                           Table 3

                           ). Furthermore, the sensor exhibited good stability and reproducibility, making it suitable for practical applications.
